{"id":14881396,"mediaExerciseId":"5bbdc3d0-b3d2-4608-a741-d4e45d20988a","exerciseName":"9","chapterName":"13","chapterTitle":"Return, Risk, and The Security Market Line","groupId":612375,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":451,"solutions":[{"id":5992587,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this exercise, we are asked to discuss alpha. \n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":28,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/7d37570ccdafc37eee0303793c0a1c6d/16c99b578340bae818c2954f22b9a665/lateximg_large.png","width":612},"regular":{"height":15,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/7d37570ccdafc37eee0303793c0a1c6d/16c99b578340bae818c2954f22b9a665/lateximg.png","width":306}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"The **security market line** is a line that shows the correlation between the expected return and volatility of a security. In other terms, this is the capital asset pricing model (CAPM), which plots varying degrees of risk associated with different investments across the market's projected to return at any particular moment.\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":181,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/7d37570ccdafc37eee0303793c0a1c6d/7eea7d9053c27379764bae118520b5a2/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":91,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/7d37570ccdafc37eee0303793c0a1c6d/7eea7d9053c27379764bae118520b5a2/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"**Alpha** is a statistical metric that indicates when an investor has outperformed the market over a certain period. This is the vertical gap between an asset's predicted return and its actual return. \n\nAlpha is the active return on an asset, and it compares an investment's performance to a stock index that is thought to reflect the market's overall movement.\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":212,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/7d37570ccdafc37eee0303793c0a1c6d/0638e56bc879698a1c3fdc6b8921a5c4/lateximg_large.png","width":1061},"regular":{"height":107,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/7d37570ccdafc37eee0303793c0a1c6d/0638e56bc879698a1c3fdc6b8921a5c4/lateximg.png","width":531}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"A negative alpha results from an increase in the expected return because of the excess investment. When alpha is positive, investors benefit from higher-than-average returns. High alphas are the outcome of better portfolio management. On the other hand, negative alphas are the total opposite of positive alphas. ","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":179,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/7d37570ccdafc37eee0303793c0a1c6d/47ac1fb4f5cabf69b45c659530ae0114/lateximg_large.png","width":998},"regular":{"height":91,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/7d37570ccdafc37eee0303793c0a1c6d/47ac1fb4f5cabf69b45c659530ae0114/lateximg.png","width":500}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"b1f05f11-4bfe-485b-b4df-d86fb56777e5","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":4}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexabl